# RelyLoop MVP1 — environment configuration
#
# Copy this file to `.env` and edit if you need to override Compose defaults.
# Most operators do NOT need a `.env` — every var below has a `${VAR:-default}`
# fallback in `docker-compose.yml` and the secret files in `./secrets/` are
# auto-generated by `make up` (scripts/install.sh).
#
# CLAUDE.md Absolute Rule #2: real secrets (Postgres password, OpenAI key,
# GitHub token) MUST live in `./secrets/<name>` files mounted as Docker
# secrets. Bare env vars (`OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...`) are NOT supported — they
# leak into `docker inspect`, container logs, and `ps` output.
#
# This `.env` is for non-secret Compose substitutions only.

# --- Postgres ----------------------------------------------------------
# (No env vars — `./secrets/postgres_password` + `./secrets/database_url`
# are generated by scripts/install.sh on first `make up`.)

# --- Redis -------------------------------------------------------------
# REDIS_URL is hard-coded in docker-compose.yml to `redis://redis:6379/0`
# (the in-Compose hostname). Override only when running the API outside
# the Compose network (rare in MVP1).

# --- Local LLM (Option B) ----------------------------------------------
# `ollama`        → NATIVE-first: install Ollama + `ollama pull qwen3.5:4b`,
#                   then `RELYLOOP_LLM=ollama make up` detects your host Ollama
#                   (Metal-fast on macOS) and wires the app at it. If none is
#                   found it prints guidance and comes up LLM-free.
# `ollama-docker` → slow zero-install Docker fallback (CPU-only on macOS).
# Default OFF (no LLM). IGNORED when OPENAI_BASE_URL below is set (Option C wins).
# RELYLOOP_LLM=ollama
# Model tag (any Ollama tag). Default qwen3.5:4b.
# OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen3.5:2b

# --- OpenAI / OpenAI-compatible endpoint (Option C) --------------------
# Point at any OpenAI-compatible endpoint; the API uses these for
# judgment generation, digest narrative, and chat orchestration.
# Leaving OPENAI_BASE_URL UNSET keeps the cloud default (api.openai.com)
# and lets RELYLOOP_LLM=ollama (Option B) work. SETTING it = Option C and
# disables the bundled LLM. So it stays commented out by default:
#   OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://host.docker.internal:11434/v1   # native Ollama (Metal)
#   OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://host.docker.internal:1234/v1    # LM Studio (Metal)
#   OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://host.docker.internal:8000/v1    # vLLM / TGI
#   OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1              # OpenAI cloud
# OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1

# Default models — judgment + digest use OPENAI_MODEL; the chat orchestrator
# uses OPENAI_MODEL_CHAT (cost-sensitive). Always pin to dated tags
# (CLAUDE.md Absolute Rule #8 forbids floating tags like "gpt-4o").
# Left COMMENTED so a copied .env doesn't force cloud model names onto the
# bundled Ollama (Option B) — install.sh defaults these to ${OLLAMA_MODEL:-
# qwen3.5:4b} under Option B, and Compose applies the cloud defaults
# (gpt-4o-2024-08-06 / gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18) otherwise. Uncomment to pin.
# OPENAI_MODEL=gpt-4o-2024-08-06
# OPENAI_MODEL_CHAT=gpt-4o-mini-2024-07-18

# Rolling 24h spend cap (USD). 0 disables the budget guard.
# (Enforcement lands at MVP2 with `audit_log` + budget metrics.)
OPENAI_DAILY_BUDGET_USD=10.0

# --- GitHub (per-repo PATs, used by feat_github_pr_worker) -------------
# GitHub PATs are NOT global. Each config_repo row carries its own `auth_ref`
# field naming a `./secrets/<auth_ref>` file. Register a config_repo via
# `POST /api/v1/config-repos` with an explicit auth_ref, then drop the PAT
# at `./secrets/<auth_ref>` (chmod 600). See
# `docs/04_security/github-token-handling.md` for rotation procedure.

# --- Cluster credentials (optional) ------------------------------------
# Populate `./secrets/cluster_credentials.yaml` with per-cluster credentials
# when registering non-local clusters via `POST /api/v1/clusters`
# (lands with `infra_adapter_elastic`).

# --- Elasticsearch / OpenSearch knobs (local Compose) ------------------
# Heap size for the local ES + OpenSearch containers. On a 16 GB laptop
# 512m is comfortable; bump to 1024m if you index large corpora.
ES_HEAP_SIZE=512m

# --- Study lifecycle defaults (feat_study_lifecycle Phase 2) ---------
# Fallbacks the orchestrator reads when `studies.config.parallelism` /
# `studies.config.trial_timeout_s` are absent from a study's payload.
# The API layer does NOT materialize these into the stored row — the
# keys stay omitted so infra_optuna_eval's pruner key-presence contract
# (explicit-override semantics) remains intact.
STUDIES_DEFAULT_PARALLELISM=4
STUDIES_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT_S=60

# --- Chat agent (feat_chat_agent) --------------------------------------
# Per-request timeout (seconds) for the chat orchestrator's OpenAI client.
# OPENAI_BASE_URL can point at any OpenAI-compatible endpoint, so this
# bounds how long a slow/hostile upstream can hold a streaming worker
# (vs the SDK's 600s default) across the tool loop. Range 10–600.
# OPENAI_CHAT_HTTP_TIMEOUT_S=120

# --- feat_github_pr_worker ---------------------------------------------
# Base URL of THIS RelyLoop install — used by the PR worker to construct
# study-detail links in PR bodies (e.g. `{base}/studies/{study_id}`).
# Unset → links are omitted from the PR body (graceful degradation).
# RELYLOOP_BASE_URL=https://relyloop.internal.example.com

# Bot identity for commits opened by the PR worker against the operator's
# config repo. Operator MUST override the email in production with the
# install-domain bot address. Defaults are placeholders so dev installs
# don't ship a real-looking address.
# RELYLOOP_GIT_AUTHOR_NAME=relyloop-bot
# RELYLOOP_GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL=relyloop-bot@your-company.com

# --- feat_github_webhook -----------------------------------------------
# Cron cadence (in minutes) for the reconcile_pr_state worker, which polls
# GitHub for PR-state changes on `proposals` that webhook delivery missed.
# Default 15 covers the spec's 15-minute SLA. Operators with low PR volume
# may raise this to reduce GitHub API spend. Story 3.1 will narrow valid
# values to a whitelist of cron-expressible cadences.
# RELYLOOP_PR_POLL_MINUTES=15

# --- feat_judgments_periodic_resume_sweep ------------------------------
# Cron cadence (in minutes) for the resume_stuck_judgment_lists worker,
# which re-enqueues `judgment_lists.status='generating'` rows whose initial
# Arq enqueue failed (e.g., transient Redis outage). Default 15 matches
# RELYLOOP_PR_POLL_MINUTES so operators have one mental model for cron
# settings. Same whitelist of cron-expressible cadences applies (see
# backend.workers.pr_reconcile.SUPPORTED_POLL_MINUTES).
# RELYLOOP_JUDGMENTS_RESUME_SWEEP_MINUTES=15
#
# Maximum re-enqueue attempts per (judgment_list_id, UTC day). When this
# cap trips the cron skips the row and emits a `judgment_resume_capped`
# WARN log — the signal that a stuck row is structurally broken (bad
# rubric, missing query template, etc.) and needs operator inspection.
# Raise to ~96 if operators have legitimately long-running judgment
# generation jobs whose ticks exhaust the cap before completion; see
# spec §10 Threat 5 for the recovery model.
# RELYLOOP_JUDGMENTS_RESUME_MAX_PER_DAY=24

# --- Selective engine startup ------------------------------------------
# feat_selective_engine_startup_and_demo Story 1.2.
#
# By default `make up` boots all three search engines (Elasticsearch,
# OpenSearch, Apache Solr) so the full demo experience works out of the
# box. If you're only evaluating RelyLoop against one engine, set
# RELYLOOP_ENGINES to a comma-separated subset of {es, os, solr} below.
# The unselected engines are never pulled, never started, and never
# probed — dramatically reducing first-run wall-clock (each skipped
# engine saves a hundreds-of-MB image pull plus a JVM boot + healthcheck
# wait).
#
# Allowed values:
#   es    → Elasticsearch
#   os    → OpenSearch
#   solr  → Apache Solr
#
# Examples:
#   RELYLOOP_ENGINES=es                 # ES only — fastest single-engine startup
#   RELYLOOP_ENGINES=es,solr            # ES + Solr; skip OpenSearch
#   RELYLOOP_ENGINES=es,os,solr         # default; same as leaving this unset
#
# Whitespace tolerated (`es, os` works); duplicates deduplicated.
# Unknown engine names exit 1 with a clear error message before any
# `docker compose` invocation. Empty / unset → default `es,os,solr`.
#
# Trade-off: the "Reset to demo state" button on the home dashboard only
# offers running engines, and the demo data only covers selected
# scenarios. The other engines' demo scenarios appear as "you excluded"
# in the partial-completion summary, not as failures.
#
# DX hazard: this var is translated into COMPOSE_PROFILES by install.sh.
# Running `docker compose up -d` directly (bypassing `make up`) WITHOUT
# setting COMPOSE_PROFILES will skip all three engines — Compose treats
# profile-gated services as opt-in by default. Either always go through
# `make up` (recommended), or set `COMPOSE_PROFILES=es,os,solr` in your
# shell first. See docs/03_runbooks/local-dev.md "Selecting a subset of
# engines".
# RELYLOOP_ENGINES=es,os,solr

# --- Selecting an engine version ----------------------------------------
#
# Pin one or more engines to a specific supported version at install time.
# Useful when evaluating RelyLoop against the version your production
# cluster runs (e.g. an ES 8.x cluster you're migrating from). Default
# unset → the matrix's latest-major default applies, identical to today's
# behavior. install.sh validates each set value against the curated
# matrix BEFORE any `docker compose pull` — unknown values exit 1 with
# a clear stderr message.
#
# Allowed values per engine — see backend/app/core/engine_versions.py
# ENGINE_VERSION_MATRIX (the source of truth):
#
#   elasticsearch: 9.4.1, 8.15.3
#   opensearch:    3.6.0, 2.18.0
#   solr:          10.0,  9.7
#
# Matrix bound is the adapter compatibility window per
# docs/01_architecture/adapters.md (ES 8.x+9.x, OpenSearch 2.x+3.x,
# Solr 9.x+10.x). Out-of-window tags are not offered — Solr's runtime
# version-floor at backend/app/adapters/solr.py would abort the probe
# outright; ES/OS would be an untested compatibility claim.
#
# Examples:
#   RELYLOOP_ES_VERSION=8.15.3      # ES 8.x evaluator path
#   RELYLOOP_OS_VERSION=2.18.0      # OpenSearch 2.x evaluator path
#   RELYLOOP_SOLR_VERSION=9.7       # Solr 9.x evaluator path
#
# The matrix's first entry per engine is the Compose `:-` default — keep
# the matrix and the docker-compose.yml `${X_IMAGE_TAG:-<default>}`
# literals in sync. CI guard at scripts/ci/verify_engine_version_matrix_parity.sh
# enforces this on every PR.
#
# RELYLOOP_ES_VERSION=8.15.3
# RELYLOOP_OS_VERSION=2.18.0
# RELYLOOP_SOLR_VERSION=9.7

# --- Corporate registry proxy (Artifactory, etc.) ----------------------
# Override the upstream registry for both (a) the Dockerfile base images
# (`python:3.14-slim`, `node:26-bookworm-slim`) AND (b) the pulled Compose
# service images (`postgres`, `redis`, `elasticsearch`, `opensearch`, `solr`)
# so an air-gapped or proxy-only environment can pull everything through a
# corporate mirror without editing the Dockerfiles or compose file. (The
# api/ui/worker/migrate images are built locally, not pulled, so they're
# unaffected.) Trailing slash is REQUIRED — the FROM/COPY/image lines
# concatenate the value directly onto the image reference.
#
# Single-proxy setup (most common Artifactory layout):
#   BASE_REGISTRY=artifactory.example.com/
#   GHCR_REGISTRY=artifactory.example.com/
#
# Separate proxies per upstream:
#   BASE_REGISTRY=docker.proxy.corp/
#   GHCR_REGISTRY=ghcr.proxy.corp/
#
# Empty / unset → unchanged behavior (Docker Hub + ghcr.io/astral-sh/uv).
# Defaults live in docker-compose.yml's `build.args` block.
# BASE_REGISTRY=
# GHCR_REGISTRY=ghcr.io/

# --- Corporate package registry mirror (npm / PyPI) --------------------
# DIFFERENT from the HTTP proxy below. Some corporate networks let the proxy
# REACH the public package registries (TLS succeeds) but FORBID them by
# policy, so the build fails with a 403 even though the proxy is configured:
#   npm error code E403 / 403 Forbidden - GET https://registry.npmjs.org/pnpm
#   (PyPI analog: 403 Forbidden from pypi.org during `uv sync`)
# The fix is to point npm/pnpm and uv at your internal Artifactory / Nexus
# virtual repo instead of the public registry. Empty / unset → public
# registries (unchanged behavior). Trailing-path shape varies by mirror;
# ask your Artifactory admin for the npm + PyPI virtual-repo URLs.
#
#   NPM_CONFIG_REGISTRY=https://artifactory.your-corp.com/api/npm/npm-virtual/
#   UV_DEFAULT_INDEX=https://artifactory.your-corp.com/api/pypi/pypi-virtual/simple
#
# If the mirror requires auth, mount an .npmrc with the `_authToken` line (npm)
# and set `UV_DEFAULT_INDEX` to an authenticated URL (uv). See
# docs/03_runbooks/corporate-network-install.md §"Package-registry 403".
# NPM_CONFIG_REGISTRY=https://registry.npmjs.org/
# UV_DEFAULT_INDEX=https://pypi.org/simple

# --- Corporate HTTP proxy (apt / PyPI / npm + runtime egress) ----------
# Routes outbound HTTP through a corporate proxy. Honored at BOTH:
#   - build time — apt-get, uv sync, npm/pnpm install RUN steps
#   - run time   — FastAPI → OpenAI, Arq → GitHub, ES/OpenSearch/Solr HTTP
#
# Empty / unset → no proxy (unchanged behavior).
#
# ⚠️ SHELL OVERRIDES THIS FILE. Docker Compose resolves `${no_proxy:-}` from
# the shell environment FIRST and only falls back to this .env when the shell
# doesn't define it. Corporate machines often export `no_proxy`/`http_proxy`
# globally (~/.zshrc, /etc/profile, MDM) — that value WINS and your edit here
# is silently ignored. Authoritative check is the running container, not .env:
#   docker compose exec api env | grep -i no_proxy   # must list elasticsearch,opensearch,solr
# If it doesn't match this file, set the value in your shell (export it, then
# `docker compose up -d --force-recreate api worker`). See
# docs/03_runbooks/corporate-network-install.md §7.
#
# IMPORTANT — `no_proxy` MUST include the Compose service names. Without
# them, the worker's HTTP call to `http://elasticsearch:9200` (and similar
# in-network calls) gets routed to the corporate proxy, which has no path
# to those Compose-internal hostnames. The default value below bakes them
# in; if you set `no_proxy` manually, include
# `postgres,redis,elasticsearch,opensearch,solr,api,worker,migrate`.
#
# Common gotchas:
#   - `169.254.169.254` is the EC2/cloud metadata service — always include
#     so cloud-instance metadata lookups skip the proxy.
#   - `10.0.0.0/8` covers internal VPC traffic.
#   - `host.docker.internal` — local-LLM dev (Ollama / LM Studio / vLLM via
#     `OPENAI_BASE_URL=http://host.docker.internal:…`) needs this exempted
#     or the proxy intercepts the local-machine call.
#
# --- Corporate CA cert (TLS-interception proxies) ---------------------
# If your corporate HTTPS proxy intercepts traffic with an internal CA
# (you'll see `SELF_SIGNED_CERT_IN_CHAIN` or similar TLS errors during
# build), the cert needs to land at:
#   ./secrets/corp_ca.crt
#
# Recommended: 'make corp-ca-extract' probes the live TLS chain and saves
# the corp root CA to that path automatically — no file paths or keychain
# spelunking needed. Then 'make up' installs it into the image trust
# store at build time. Works on macOS, Linux, and WSL.
#
# Manual fallback (when the auto-extract picks the wrong cert): drop your
# PEM-format corp CA cert at ./secrets/corp_ca.crt directly. Empty
# placeholder file is fine — operators outside corp networks don't need
# to do anything. See docs/03_runbooks/corporate-network-install.md.
#
# Both case variants (http_proxy + HTTP_PROXY etc.) are written by Compose
# build.args and the Dockerfile ENV block — Linux tooling is split on
# which convention it reads.
# http_proxy=http://http.proxy.your-corp.com:8000
# https_proxy=http://http.proxy.your-corp.com:8000
# no_proxy=your-corp.com,.your-corp-cloud.com,localhost,127.0.0.1,10.0.0.0/8,169.254.169.254,host.docker.internal,postgres,redis,elasticsearch,opensearch,solr,api,worker,migrate

# --- Build-time only --------------------------------------------------
# RELYLOOP_GIT_SHA is injected at `docker buildx build` via --build-arg.
# `make up` propagates the current short-SHA when invoking compose.
